description.value: Model (scale 1:2) of weir of draw door type, as used on the upper Thames; constructed from drawings lent by the Conservators of the River Thames

Draw Door Weir, 1872. This is a model of an adjustable weir erected by the Thames Conservancy. Such means of raising the water level in a river provided for the extraction of water for filtration and purification for public supply; or for agricultural irrigation, industrial use or to reduce the water level downstream. Even in England, much of civilised living depends on such devices. In the Netherlands the whole country has depended on water control for six or seven hundred years. The Thames is tidal river upstream as far as Teddington (Tide-end-town), but, above there, twenty or thirty such weirs have been constructed in the last century.
